CSS alone cannot directly change the state of a checkbox (such as unchecking it) in response to user interactions like clicking a hyperlink. CSS is primarily used for styling and lacks the capability to perform state manipulations based on events. However, you can achieve the desired functionality by combining HTML, CSS, and a small amount of JavaScript. Below, I'll outline how to uncheck a checkbox when a user clicks on a hyperlink.

## Step-by-Step Solution

### 1. HTML Structure

First, set up your HTML with a checkbox and a hyperlink. Assign unique IDs to each element to reference them in JavaScript.

```html
<!DOCTYPE html>
<html lang="en">
<head>
  <meta charset="UTF-8">
  <title>Uncheck Checkbox Example</title>
  <link rel="stylesheet" href="styles.css">
</head>
<body>
  <label for="myCheckbox">
    <input type="checkbox" id="myCheckbox">
    Check me
  </label>

  <a href="#" id="uncheckLink">Uncheck the box</a>

  <script src="script.js"></script>
</body>
</html>
```

### 2. CSS Styling (Optional)

While CSS can't manipulate the checkbox state, you can style the checkbox and hyperlink to enhance the user experience.

```css
/* styles.css */
body {
  font-family: Arial, sans-serif;
  padding: 20px;
}

label {
  display: block;
  margin-bottom: 10px;
  cursor: pointer;
}

a {
  color: blue;
  text-decoration: underline;
  cursor: pointer;
}

a:hover {
  color: darkblue;
}
```

### 3. JavaScript to Handle the Event

Use JavaScript to add an event listener to the hyperlink. When the link is clicked, the script will uncheck the checkbox.

```javascript
// script.js
document.addEventListener('DOMContentLoaded', () => {
  const checkbox = document.getElementById('myCheckbox');
  const uncheckLink = document.getElementById('uncheckLink');

  uncheckLink.addEventListener('click', (event) => {
    event.preventDefault(); // Prevent default link behavior
    checkbox.checked = false; // Uncheck the checkbox
  });
});
```

### 4. Putting It All Together

When the user clicks the hyperlink labeled "Uncheck the box":

1. The JavaScript `click` event listener intercepts the click.
2. `event.preventDefault()` stops the browser from following the `href="#"` link.
3. `checkbox.checked = false;` programmatically unchecks the checkbox.

## Complete Example

Here's the complete code for reference.

### `index.html`

```html
<!DOCTYPE html>
<html lang="en">
<head>
  <meta charset="UTF-8">
  <title>Uncheck Checkbox Example</title>
  <link rel="stylesheet" href="styles.css">
</head>
<body>
  <label for="myCheckbox">
    <input type="checkbox" id="myCheckbox">
    Check me
  </label>

  <a href="#" id="uncheckLink">Uncheck the box</a>

  <script src="script.js"></script>
</body>
</html>
```

### `styles.css`

```css
body {
  font-family: Arial, sans-serif;
  padding: 20px;
}

label {
  display: block;
  margin-bottom: 10px;
  cursor: pointer;
}

a {
  color: blue;
  text-decoration: underline;
  cursor: pointer;
}

a:hover {
  color: darkblue;
}
```

### `script.js`

```javascript
document.addEventListener('DOMContentLoaded', () => {
  const checkbox = document.getElementById('myCheckbox');
  const uncheckLink = document.getElementById('uncheckLink');

  uncheckLink.addEventListener('click', (event) => {
    event.preventDefault(); // Prevent default link behavior
    checkbox.checked = false; // Uncheck the checkbox
  });
});
```

## Alternative Approach: Using a Label as a Toggle

If you prefer to minimize JavaScript, you can use a hidden checkbox to control the state and toggle it with labels. However, this approach is limited and less flexible.

### HTML Example

```html
<!DOCTYPE html>
<html lang="en">
<head>
  <meta charset="UTF-8">
  <title>Toggle Checkbox with Label</title>
  <style>
    #myCheckbox {
      display: none;
    }
    #myCheckbox:checked + label.toggleLabel::after {
      content: " (Checked)";
      color: green;
    }
    #myCheckbox:not(:checked) + label.toggleLabel::after {
      content: " (Unchecked)";
      color: red;
    }
  </style>
</head>
<body>
  <input type="checkbox" id="myCheckbox">
  <label for="myCheckbox" class="toggleLabel">Check me</label>

  <label for="myCheckbox" style="cursor: pointer; color: blue; text-decoration: underline;">
    Uncheck the box
  </label>
</body>
</html>
```

### Explanation

- The checkbox is hidden using `display: none;`.
- Two labels are associated with the same checkbox using the `for` attribute.
- Clicking the first label toggles the checkbox.
- Clicking the second label also toggles the checkbox, effectively acting as a link to uncheck it when it's checked.

**Note:** This method toggles the checkbox state and doesn't specifically uncheck it. It also relies on the user clicking the appropriate label, which might not be as intuitive.

## Conclusion

While CSS alone cannot uncheck a checkbox in response to events like clicking a hyperlink, combining HTML, CSS, and a small amount of JavaScript provides a straightforward and effective solution. This approach ensures better control and flexibility over user interactions and state management.
